```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    PiezoSensor -> ChargeAmplifier -> LowPassFilter -> AntiAliasingFilter -> ADC -> Microcontroller -> OutputInterface;

    // Labeling for better understanding
    PiezoSensor [label="Piezoelectric Accelerometer"];
    ChargeAmplifier [label="Charge Amplifier"];
    LowPassFilter [label="Low-Pass Filter\n(0.25 Hz -3dB)"];
    AntiAliasingFilter [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter\n(< 4Hz)"];
    ADC [label="Analog to Digital Converter"];
    Microcontroller [label="Microcontroller\n(Data Processing)"];
    OutputInterface [label="Output Interface\n(Display, USB, etc.)"];
}
```

```Explanations
Piezoelectric Accelerometer: This block contains the piezoelectric sensor that generates a charge proportional to the acceleration experienced due to vibration. The sensor has a sensitivity of 100 pC/g, which will be the primary input for the charge amplifier.

Charge Amplifier: A charge amplifier converts the high-impedance charge output from the piezoelectric sensor into a low-impedance voltage signal suitable for further processing. It has a high input impedance to ensure minimal charge leakage from the sensor and uses a feedback capacitor and resistor to define the gain and bandwidth. The gain will be set to achieve a 1 Vpp output for the given peak acceleration.

Low-Pass Filter: This is designed to have a -3 dB point at 0.25 Hz to attenuate any frequencies below the interest range and to establish a stable DC level against low-frequency drifts. This will help to maintain the offset voltage within the desired 10 mV range.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: Before sampling the signal with an ADC, an anti-aliasing filter is necessary to remove any high-frequency content that could alias into the frequency band of interest when sampled. Since the system is designed for up to 2 Hz, this filter will have a cutoff frequency just above twice this maximum frequency, generally around 4 Hz to meet the Nyquist criterion.

ADC: The analog-to-digital converter digitizes the conditioned analog signal from the accelerometer for digital processing. The ADC resolution and sampling rate should be selected based on the requirements of the measurement precision and the maximum frequency of interest.

Microcontroller: The microcontroller serves as the central processing unit for the device. It controls the ADC, processes the digitized data according to the measurement requirements, and can be programmed to compensate for any system offsets or calibration needs.

Output Interface: This block represents the user interface and data output mechanisms of the device. It can include a display for real-time measurement visualization or various communication interfaces like USB or Bluetooth for data logging and further analysis on a computer or mobile device.
```

